{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585756"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:17:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:17:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15010"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15010","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15010"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.85,0.05,0.07,0.02,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7698"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66849"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7698"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15010"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52303"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"},{"type":"tags","id":"5264"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18810"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18813"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66849"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETetracyclines are a class of broad-spectrum antibiotics commonly used in clinical practice.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of tetracyclines?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Binds to 30S ribosomal subunit to inhibit protein synthesis","Inhibits bacterial cell wall synthesis","Disrupts bacterial cell membrane integrity","Blocks bacterial DNA gyrase","Interferes with bacterial folic acid synthesis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETetracyclines work by \u003Cstrong\u003Ebinding to the 30S ribosomal subunit\u003C/strong\u003E to inhibit protein synthesis. This prevents aminoacyl transfer RNA from attaching to the ribosome, making tetracyclines bacteriostatic antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms belong to other antibiotic classes:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of cell wall synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - mechanism of beta-lactam antibiotics (penicillins, cephalosporins)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisruption of cell membrane integrity\u003C/strong\u003E - mechanism of polymyxins\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking DNA gyrase\u003C/strong\u003E - mechanism of fluoroquinolones\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterference with folic acid synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - mechanism of sulfonamides and trimethoprim\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETetracyclines are used to treat various infections including respiratory tract infections, urinary tract infections, and acne. Common examples include doxycycline, minocycline, and tetracycline.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Tetracyclines work by binding to the 30S ribosomal subunit to inhibit bacterial protein synthesis","Tetracyclines prevent aminoacyl transfer RNA attachment to ribosomes, making them bacteriostatic","Common tetracyclines include doxycycline, minocycline, and tetracycline"],"references":["Nguyen F, Starosta AL, Arenz S, Sohmen D, D\u00f6nh\u00f6fer A, Wilson DN. Tetracycline antibiotics and resistance mechanisms. Biol Chem. 2014 May;395(5):559-75. doi: 10.1515/hsz-2013-0292. PMID: 24497223.","Hauser, A. (2018). Antibiotic basics for clinicians. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012)